\begin_layout Section
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

-reactor platform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

-reactor platform is invented here at CINF and is originally published in
 2009 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Henriksen2009"

\end_inset

.
 The device itself and the fabrication process is described in details in
 Toke Henriksen's Ph.D.
 thesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Toke-phd"

\end_inset

.
 In summary the device is a clean-room fabricated sillicon chip with two
 gas-inlets, a outlet carrying the main gas-flow out of the reactor and
 a reactor area with a small outlet capillary which is connected to a mass
 spectrometer.
 Once the catalyst to be tested is positioned in the reactor area (this
 can be done in a number of ways), the reactor is closed by anodically bonding
 a pyrex lid to the sample.
 The clever idea about the design is that even though most of the incoming
 gas-flow is pumped away imidiately, every molecule that actually enters
 the reactor area, will be led into the mass spectrometer and thus the sensitivi
ty of the device is very high.
 The design shows a number of advantages compared to a traditional catalytic
 reactors:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The total volume of the reactor is just 240
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

nL, meaning that we are able to measure on very small amounts of catalyst,
 this could for example be samples produced in a cluster source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Only very small amounts of the reacting gasses needs to be mixed, meaning
 that potentially explosive mixtures can be measured without rising safety
 issues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The thermal mass is very low, and the temperature of the reactor can therefore
 be raised very quickly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The glass lid of the reactor gives easy optical contact to the catalyst,
 meaning that the reactor can be used for photo-catalysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course the design also has it downsides, the most import problem is properly
 the fact that it is almost impossible to apply any traditional surface
 science technique on the catalyst because the reactor it is hermetically
 sealed and no easy way of opening the lid is known.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

-reactor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The actual 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

-reactor chip is CleanRoom fabricated Si-based and has a size of 20x16
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset

mm .
 The reactor consists of two inlets, a mixing zone allowing for diffusional
 mixing of reactants, an outlet, a reactor volume of 240
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset

nL and a 
\begin_inset Formula $5.4\,\mu$
\end_inset

m wide, 
\begin_inset Formula $3\,\mu$
\end_inset

m high and 
\begin_inset Formula $1500\,\mu$
\end_inset

m long capillary used for sniffing gases from the reactor volume.
 The reactor is sealed by anodically bonding of a pyrex lid to the Si reactor
 and is able to operate in a pressure range of 0 to at least 5
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

bar.
 The reaction gases are supplied to the two inlets by flow controllers capable
 of controlling the gas flow from 0-10 mL/min.
 The capillary flow is fed into a quadropole mass-spectrometer (QMS) for
 analysis while any surplus of gas from the inlets is passed directly through
 to the outlet via a pressure controller allowing control of reactor pressure.
 The design makes sure that all gases exposed to the catalyst under investigatio
n are measured by the QMS ensuring an extremely high sensitivity of the
 system.
 During experiments the chip is mounted in a metal block wich is connected
 to the main tubings for gas-handling.
 The sealing between the chip and the metal block is done by o-rings, the
 typical material of choise is Kalrez due to its ability to go to very high
 temperatures.
 For low temperature operation, also Viton can be considered.
 Unfortunately rubber o-rings are not leak-tight especially not when they
 are heated, this means that we have an inflow of air across all four o-rings,
 this could be unfortunate in situation where oxygen is not wanted, e.g.
 methanol synthesis.
 Also, the air inflow through the o-ring sealing the outlet-capillary complicate
s interpretration of data a lot since it will give a background of air on
 top of the signal from the product gas.
 To eliminate both problems the o-rings are continously flush by a flow
 of Argon, if the flow is chosen sufficiently high, it will almost completely
 out-compete the air-inflow and result in a pure Argon inflow, which is
 at lot more acceptable.
 Another solution to the problem is to evacuate the entire sourrindings
 of the metal block, this option is discussed later in this chapter.
\end_layout

