The setup has several problems which it was needed to adress before the
 setup was really ready to take do measurements beyond proof-of-concept
 measurements.
 First of all, it is evient from figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:old_old_setup"

\end_inset

 that all the gas-handling is pump directly by a rouging pump.
 This means that the the system will be constantly contaminated by oil residues
 from the pump which is the primary constituent in the residual pressure
 from a roughing pump.
 This also means that it is impossible to do a proper pump-down of the capillary
 before opening to the mass-spectrometer and thus the background pressure
 in the main chamber will typically be rather high, primarily because of
 water, residual air and perhaps oil from the roughing pump depending on
 how far the capillary was pumped down.
 Another problem is the valves in front of the flow-controllers.
 It is well known that flow-controllers are not very leak-tight across the
 device even when the flow is set to zero.
 This means that one wants to eliminate the background of the gasses available
 on the setup, one needs to close the valve in front of it, however with
 a manual valve, this makes it impossible to eliminate backgrounds from
 gasses that are actually used during the experiment.
\end_layout

